[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(32) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "That the saying of Jesus might be fulfilled.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Comp. Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Signifying what death he should die.—Better, signifying by what manner of death He should die. (Comp. Note on John 10:32.) For the prediction of the manner of death, comp. John 3:14; John 12:32; and Note on Matthew 20:19. If the Jews had possessed the power to put Him to death, they would have condemned Him on the technical charge of blasphemy, for which the punishment was stoning. (Comp. John 8:59; John 10:31; and Acts 7:51 et seq.) Crucifixion was not a Jewish punishment, and it was in the fact that He was executed, not by Jewish authority and on the charge of blasphemy, but by Roman authority and on a charge of Majestas (high treason), that His own prophecy of the manner of His death was fulfilled.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Signifying what death he should die.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "signifying by what manner of death He should die.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (Comp. Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 10:32",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) For the prediction of the manner of death, comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 3:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 12:32",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; and Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 20:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". If the Jews had possessed the power to put Him to death, they would have condemned Him on the technical charge of blasphemy, for which the punishment was stoning. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 8:59",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 10:31",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 7:51",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "et seq.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") Crucifixion was not a Jewish punishment, and it was in the fact that He was executed, not by Jewish authority and on the charge of blasphemy, but by Roman authority and on a charge of Majestas (high treason), that His own prophecy of the manner of His death was fulfilled.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "18:28-32 It was unjust to put one to death who had done so much good, therefore the Jews were willing to save themselves from reproach. Many fear the scandal of an ill thing, more than the sin of it. Christ had said he should be delivered to the Gentiles, and they should put him to death; hereby that saying was fulfilled. He had said that he should be crucified, lifted up. If the Jews had judged him by their law, he had been stoned; crucifying never was used among the Jews. It is determined concerning us, though not discovered to us, what death we shall die: this should free us from disquiet about that matter. Lord, what, when, and how, thou hast appointed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That the saying of Jesus ... - To wit, that he would be delivered into the hands of the Gentiles and be crucified, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 20:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Neither of these things would have happened if he had been put to death in the way that the Jews first contemplated, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Though it should be admitted that they had the power, in religious cases, to do this, yet in such a case it would not have been done, as Jesus predicted, by the Gentiles; and even if it should be admitted that they had the right to take life, yet they had not the right to do it by crucifixion. This was particularly a Roman punishment. And thus it was ordered, in the providence of God, that the prediction of Jesus in both these respects was fulfilled. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "32. That the saying … might be fulfilled which he spake, signifying what death he should die—that is, by crucifixion (Joh 12:32, 33; Mt 20:19); which being a Roman mode of execution, could only be carried into effect by order of the governor. (The Jewish mode in such cases as this was by stoning).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Christ had before this time told his disciples that he should die, and that by the death of the cross, as we read, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Matthew 20:19",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 20:19",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God by his providence ordereth things accordingly, to let us know that the Scripture might be fulfilled to every tittle. Crucifying was no Jewish but a Roman death; had the Jews put him to death, they would have stoned him; but he must remove the curse from us, by being made ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a curse for us, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " being ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hanged on a tree, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which was looked upon as an accursed death, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Galatians 3:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 3:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Jews therefore knowing nothing of this counsel of God, yet execute it by refusing themselves to put him to death, and putting it off to Pilate, though possibly their design was but to avoid the odium of it. Thus God maketh the wrath of men to praise him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That the saying of Jesus might be fulfilled,.... That he should be delivered by the Jews to the Gentiles, to crucify him; and that he should be lifted up from the earth, and as the serpent upon the pole: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "which he spake, signifying what death he should die;  Matthew 20:19 and which was brought about this way, by the providence of God conducting this whole affair; and was cheerfully submitted to by Christ, in great love to his people, to redeem them from the curse of the law, being hereby made a curse for them. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "which he spake, signifying what death he should die;  ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 20:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " and which was brought about this way, by the providence of God conducting this whole affair; and was cheerfully submitted to by Christ, in great love to his people, to redeem them from the curse of the law, being hereby made a curse for them. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "That the saying of Jesus might be fulfilled, which he spake, {c} signifying what death he should die.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "That the saying of Jesus might be fulfilled, which he spake, ",
